why the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">Government</ENAMEX>'s asserted interest in "preventing [public
radio] <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">stations</ENAMEX> from becoming a privileged outlet for the political
and ideological opinions of station <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">owners</ENAMEX> and <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">managers</ENAMEX>," <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">468</NUMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">U.</ENAMEX>
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">S.</ENAMEX>, at <NUMEX TYPE="MONEY">396</NUMEX> (internal quotation marks omitted), was insubstantial
and thus could not justify the statute's restriction on
<ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">editorializing</ENAMEX>. Even worse for the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Court</ENAMEX>, after invalidating the
restriction on this conventional <ENAMEX TYPE="LAW">First Amendment</ENAMEX> ground, <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">League of</ENAMEX>
